<hr><b>No diff available--this is the first major revision.</b>
(no other diffs)<hr>Add paragraphs by simply typing the text into the editing box. The basic rules are:
<p>
<UL>
<li> Don't indent paragraphs -- indentation is actually a special formatting code. Start all normal paragraphs at the far left edge of the editing box, with no leading spaces.
<li> Don't use <b>[Enter]</b> to break lines in mid-sentence. Let the program take care of line wrapping and text-filling as needed, to accommodate the visitor's browser size.
<li> Use blank lines to separate paragraphs, so that what you see in the editing box will (roughly) resemble the final formatted page.
<li> Use a horizontal rule (if you wish -- this is most often a personal style matter) to separate topics or sections on a single page. Add a rule by putting four hyphens (----) together at the very beginning of a line.
<li> For <b>preformatted</b> or monospace font text,  one way is to indent the line by one or more spaces.
</UL>
<p>
<PRE>
    Preformatted text uses a monospaced font, helpful
    for exact alignment of numerical columns, or for
    creating ASCII art or diagrams. Indenting also
    preserves Wiki links, like <a href="wiki.pl?WikiWikiSandbox">WikiWikiSandbox</a>.
</PRE>
<p>
<UL>
<li> Another way is to use the HTML PRE and /PRE tags:
</UL>
<p>
<pre>
    Preformatted text uses a monospaced font, helpful
    for exact alignment of numerical columns, or for
    creating ASCII art or diagrams. Using HTML tags
    for preformatted text does not preserve Wiki links,
    like [[WikiWikiSandbox]], because nothing but line-ends are
    processed in a PRE /PRE block.
</pre>
